Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/background-message-handlers.ts (call sendResponse in handlePluginReadinessChanged)

Context:
In initBackgroundMessageHandlers (line ~811), the message listener returns `true` for ALL registered handlers:
  const handler = backgroundHandlers.get(message.type);
  if (handler) {
    handler(message as unknown as Record<string, unknown>, sendResponse);
    return true;  // ← always true for registered handlers
  }

Returning true tells Chrome to keep the message channel open waiting for sendResponse. But handlePluginReadinessChanged (line ~338) takes `_sendResponse` (underscore = intentionally unused) and never calls it:
  const handlePluginReadinessChanged: MessageHandler = (message, _sendResponse) => {
    const plugin = message.plugin;
    if (typeof plugin !== 'string' || plugin === '') return;
    (async () => { ... })().catch(...);
  };

Every plugin:readinessChanged event from content scripts leaves an orphaned message channel. Chrome eventually closes these with 'A listener indicated an asynchronous response by returning true, but the message channel closed before a response was received' errors in the extension error log.

Changes:
Rename the `_sendResponse` parameter to `sendResponse` and add `sendResponse({ ok: true })` either at the start of the handler body (before the early return) or after the async IIFE launch, matching the fire-and-forget pattern used by handleToolProgress:
  const handleToolProgress: MessageHandler = (message, sendResponse) => {
    // ... async work fire-and-forget ...
    sendResponse({ ok: true });  // always called at end
  };

The simplest correct fix — call sendResponse({ ok: true }) right after the early-return guard and async IIFE, e.g.:
  const handlePluginReadinessChanged: MessageHandler = (message, sendResponse) => {
    const plugin = message.plugin;
    if (typeof plugin !== 'string' || plugin === '') {
      sendResponse({ ok: true });
      return;
    }
    (async () => { ... })().catch(...);
    sendResponse({ ok: true });  // ← add this
  };

Constraints:
- Do NOT change initBackgroundMessageHandlers or the message listener structure.
- Do NOT change the async work logic inside the IIFE.
- Do NOT add sendResponse({ ok: true }) to any other handler (they already handle it).
- This is a 1-2 line change to handlePluginReadinessChanged only.

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/iife-injection.ts (fix host extraction in resolvePerTabSettings)

Context:
resolvePerTabSettings (line ~257) iterates over entries in `instanceMap` (Record<string, string> where values are Chrome URL patterns) to find which instance's URL pattern matches the current tab's host:

  let matchedInstance: string | undefined;
  try {
    const tabHost = new URL(tabUrl).host;
    for (const [name, pattern] of Object.entries(instanceMap)) {
      const patternHost = pattern.replace('*://', '').replace('/*', '');
      if (tabHost === patternHost) {
        matchedInstance = name;
        break;
      }
    }
  } catch { ... }

Bug: the two-step replace only removes `*://` prefix and `/*` suffix. For pattern `https://app.example.com/*`:
  1. replace('*://', '') → 'https://app.example.com/*'  (no match)
  2. replace('/*', '')  → 'https://app.example.com'     (trailing /* removed)
  3. 'app.example.com' === 'https://app.example.com' → FALSE

For pattern `*://app.example.com/*` (current working case):
  1. replace('*://', '') → 'app.example.com/*'
  2. replace('/*', '')  → 'app.example.com'
  3. 'app.example.com' === 'app.example.com' → TRUE ✓

Changes:
Replace the two-step string replace with a regex that handles all three scheme prefixes:
  // Before:
  const patternHost = pattern.replace('*://', '').replace('/*', '');

  // After:
  const patternHost = pattern.replace(/^(?:\*|https?):[\/]{2}/, '').replace(/\/.*$/, '').split(':')[0];

Or equivalently using a single regex match:
  const m = pattern.match(/^(?:\*|https?):[\/]{2}([^/]+)/);
  const patternHost = m ? m[1].split(':')[0] : '';  // split(':')[0] strips optional port

The `.split(':')[0]` strips an optional port number (e.g., `localhost:8080` → `localhost`), which the current code also handles implicitly since the original replace approach would include the port in the extracted host and the comparison would fail anyway. The new approach is equivalent for the common case but now correctly handles https:// and http:// prefixes.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the fallback behavior when matchedInstance is undefined (the warning log + `resolved[key] = ''` lines stay as-is).
- Do NOT change any other function in the file.
- The instanceMap entries are Chrome URL match patterns — they can be *://, https://, or http:// prefixed. Wildcard hosts like *.example.com do NOT appear in instanceMap (instanceMap is for specific named instances, not wildcards).
- The `tabHost` is extracted via `new URL(tabUrl).host`, which does NOT include the port for default ports (80/443) but DOES include it for non-standard ports like :8080. The pattern extraction should handle this correctly.

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/BrowserToolsCard.tsx (fix handleToolPermissionChange rollback)

Context:
The current buggy implementation uses a single ref to store pre-toggle state:
  const preToggleRef = useRef<BrowserToolState[]>([]);

  const handleToolPermissionChange = (toolName: string, newPermission: ToolPermission) => {
    const myVersion = ++toggleCounter.current;
    onToolsChange(prev => {
      preToggleRef.current = prev;  // ← OVERWRITES on every call
      return prev.map(t => (t.name === toolName ? { ...t, permission: newPermission } : t));
    });
    void setToolPermission('browser', toolName, newPermission).catch(() => {
      if (toggleCounter.current === myVersion) {
        onToolsChange(() => preToggleRef.current);  // ← reads the shared ref
      }
      showToggleError(`Failed to update ${toolName}`);
    });
  };

Bug scenario:
1. toggleA → myVersion=1, preToggleRef = [A=off, B=off] (first call, correct snapshot)
2. toggleB → myVersion=2, preToggleRef = [A=auto, B=off] (OVERWRITES snapshot)
3. toggleA fails: toggleCounter=2 ≠ 1, rollback skipped. A stuck at 'auto'.
4. toggleB fails: toggleCounter=2 = 2, rolls back to [A=auto, B=off]. A never reverted.

Reference implementation in PluginCard.tsx (the correct pattern):
  const pendingToolRollbacks = useRef<Map<number, { toolName: string; prev: ToolPermission }>>(new Map());

  const applyToolPermission = (toolName: string, newPermission: ToolPermission) => {
    const myVersion = ++toggleCounter.current;
    const currentPerm = pluginTools.find(t => t.name === toolName)?.permission ?? 'off';
    pendingToolRollbacks.current.set(myVersion, { toolName, prev: currentPerm });
    updatePluginTools(prev => prev.map(t => (t.name === toolName ? { ...t, permission: newPermission } : t)));
    void setToolPermission(plugin.name, toolName, newPermission)
      .catch(() => {
        const rollback = pendingToolRollbacks.current.get(myVersion);
        if (rollback) {
          updatePluginTools(prev =>
            prev.map(t => (t.name === rollback.toolName ? { ...t, permission: rollback.prev } : t)),
          );
        }
        showToggleError(`Failed to update ${rollback.toolName}`);
      })
      .finally(() => {
        pendingToolRollbacks.current.delete(myVersion);
      });
  };

Changes:
Adapt the PluginCard approach for BrowserToolsCard:
1. Remove `preToggleRef` and add `pendingToolRollbacks = useRef<Map<number, { toolName: string; prev: ToolPermission }>>(new Map())`
2. In handleToolPermissionChange, capture the current permission of the specific tool being changed:
   const currentPerm = tools.find(t => t.name === toolName)?.permission ?? 'off';
   pendingToolRollbacks.current.set(myVersion, { toolName, prev: currentPerm });
3. In the catch, look up the per-version rollback and apply it surgically to just that tool:
   const rollback = pendingToolRollbacks.current.get(myVersion);
   if (rollback) {
     onToolsChange(prev => prev.map(t => (t.name === rollback.toolName ? { ...t, permission: rollback.prev } : t)));
   }
4. In .finally(), delete the rollback entry: `pendingToolRollbacks.current.delete(myVersion)`
5. `handleBrowserPermissionChange` also uses its own pre-change capture (`preBrowserPermRef`), which is CORRECT — it stores the single browserPermission value (not a list) before calling `onBrowserPermissionChange`. Do NOT change handleBrowserPermissionChange.

Constraints:
- Only change handleToolPermissionChange. Do NOT touch handleBrowserPermissionChange.
- Do NOT change the myVersion guard pattern (the .catch still only fires on the last concurrent failure — that's intentional for the browser-level permission). Only handleToolPermissionChange needs the per-invocation Map.
- The `tools` variable inside `handleToolPermissionChange` comes from the `tools` prop passed to BrowserToolsCard (via `visibleTools` or direct). Access the current tool permission via the `tools` prop at call time, not from inside the updater.
- showToggleError still fires for every failure, not just the last one — keep that.

Files:
- platform/browser-extension/src/network-capture.ts (add cleanupThrottle to onDetach handler)

Context:
The onDetach handler (line ~435) currently reads:
  chrome.debugger.onDetach.addListener((source: chrome.debugger.Debuggee, _reason: string) => {
    const tabId = source.tabId;
    if (tabId !== undefined) {
      cleanupInterception(tabId);
      cleanupEmulation(tabId);
      const state = captures.get(tabId);
      if (state) clearInterval(state.pruneIntervalId);
      captures.delete(tabId);
    }
  });

The tabs.onRemoved handler (line ~421) calls all three cleanup functions:
  chrome.tabs.onRemoved.addListener((tabId: number) => {
    cleanupInterception(tabId);
    cleanupEmulation(tabId);
    cleanupThrottle(tabId);  // ← present here but missing from onDetach
    ...
  });

cleanupThrottle is exported from platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/throttle-commands.ts:
  export const cleanupThrottle = (tabId: number): void => {
    throttlingTabs.delete(tabId);
  };

Check the existing imports at the top of network-capture.ts — cleanupThrottle may not yet be imported there (it's imported in tabs.onRemoved's enclosing file context, or might be added). The import block at the top of network-capture.ts currently imports cleanupEmulation from './browser-commands/emulation-commands.js', handleFetchRequestPaused and isIntercepting from './browser-commands/interception-commands.js', and cleanupThrottle from './browser-commands/throttle-commands.js' (check if already present).

Changes:
1. Add cleanupThrottle to the import from './browser-commands/throttle-commands.js' if not already imported (check the current imports at lines 1-10 of network-capture.ts)
2. Add `cleanupThrottle(tabId);` to the onDetach handler, right after `cleanupEmulation(tabId);`:
   chrome.debugger.onDetach.addListener((source: chrome.debugger.Debuggee, _reason: string) => {
     const tabId = source.tabId;
     if (tabId !== undefined) {
       cleanupInterception(tabId);
       cleanupEmulation(tabId);
       cleanupThrottle(tabId);  // ← add this line
       const state = captures.get(tabId);
       if (state) clearInterval(state.pruneIntervalId);
       captures.delete(tabId);
     }
   });

Constraints:
- This is a 1-2 line change. Do not modify any other logic.
- Do NOT call chrome.debugger.detach in onDetach — the debugger is already detached when onDetach fires.
- Do NOT change the tabs.onRemoved handler — it already calls cleanupThrottle correctly.
- Do NOT change stopCapture — it calls chrome.debugger.detach which fires onDetach, which now calls cleanupThrottle.
